<p>I haven't heard really anyone say that this was a good idea. I have heard some say (AKA the ones who never could hack the skill) that the comprimise of the other effects still hitting moving targets was livable, but who REALLY wanted this? A bard is almost exclusivly a solo class, if you don't belive me, try one. You try twisting 4 songs and being part of the MMPORG of EQ, not that they aren't great in groups (For the other members) but you rarely get to have a conversation with a bard, he is too busy twisting to be able to type. So they had to lvl on thier own, getting carple tunnel, eye strain from focusing intensely and the huge rush and thrill that THEY did it, one of the most challenging things in the game. Sure there is good XP potential. There is ALWAYS a great potential for things in EQ if you do them well. EQ is like Life, you never wake up and say, &quot;OK, I win, nothing left to do today&quot;. But in EQ you become a master tailor, and you have huge Pp potential. You spend months of farming, thousands of Kp and Poof, you are wealthy beyond your dreams if you choose to be. same with a bard, you spend huge amounts of time learning a skill, tons of time on CR's, and even then you have a high failure rate. No matter what people say, AE kiting ISN&quot;T easy, Nor is it an unfair advantage, as a 65 druid, I can pull an AA every 15 min in PoF tables with a group, that is safe, steady not much risk XP, then you take a bard, 20 minutes per success to get 1.75 AA in PoV or more in HoH, but if you add in the times you die after 15 minutes and getting mobs down to 10% then poof... LOADING. it all evens out. If you can't put in a twisting interface that lets the bards interact with the community without manual twisting, at least stay out of the way. DOWN WITH PINK, DOWN WITH THE NERF.</p>
